{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Aditya Academy Ground | nickname = | country = India | image = | location = [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]] | establishment = 2012 | seating_capacity = n/a | end1 = | end2 = n/a | club1 = [[Karnataka cricket team]] | year1 = 2012-present | club2 = [[India national blind cricket team]] | year2 = 2012-present | date = 26 August | year = 2015 | source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/555171.html Cricinfo }} '''Aditya Academy Ground''' is a cricket ground in [[Bengaluru]], [[India]]. It was established in 2012. The ground is not a first-class venue but it is only used for [[List A cricket]], domestic under-19s or [[Blind cricket]].
In 2012, the first [[Blind cricket|T20 Blind Cricket World Cup]] was held in [[Bangalore]] and the Aditya Academy Ground was one of venue and host 19 matches of it. India defeated Pakistan by 29 runs in the final.<ref>{{cite news|title=India defeated Pakistan in first T20 Blind Cricket World Cup|url=http://www.cricketworld.com/india-beat-pakistan-to-win-blind-t20-world-cup/32994.htm|accessdate=13 December 2012|newspaper=CricketWorld|date=13 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lots of cheer as India win T20 World Cup for the Blind|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/world-t20/content/current/series/628368.html|accessdate=13 December 2012|newspaper=CricInfo|date=13 December 2012}}</ref>
In 2014, the ground hosted its first [[Vijay Hazare Trophy]] matches when [[Hyderabad cricket team]] played against [[Tamil Nadu cricket team]]. Two more [[List A]] Matches are played on this ground.<ref> [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/14/9745_a.html List A Matches] </ref>
